 "ModificationHighlight" -> False, "ColorType" -> "", "LinkTrails" -> "", 
  "ExampleCounter" -> 1, 
  "Openers" -> {
   "PrimaryExamplesSection" -> Open, "ExampleSection" -> {"0" -> Open}}, 
  "NewStyles" -> True, "CitationPopupData" -> {"2021", ""}, "ShowCitation" -> 
  False, "RootCaptions" -> "", "HeaderCoreAreaLink" -> {}, 
  "Metadata" -> {
   "built" -> "{2026, 4, 12, 18, 0, 0.274210}", 
    "history" -> {"13", "", "", ""}, "context" -> "QuantumMob`Q3`", 
    "keywords" -> {"stabilizer formalism", "Gottesman-Knill theorem"}, 
    "specialkeywords" -> {}, "tutorialcollectionlinks" -> {}, "index" -> True,
     "label" -> "Quantum Mob/ Q3 Tech Note", "language" -> "en", "paclet" -> 
    "QuantumMob/Q3", "status" -> "None", "summary" -> 
    "The Pauli group is the group of all tensor products of single-qubit \
Pauli operators. The elements of the Pauli group are called (multi-qubit) \
Pauli operators. The Clifford group is the group of all unitary operators \
that keep the Pauli group invariant (that is, map a Pauli operator to another \
Pauli operator) under conjugation. The elements of the Clifford group are \
called Clifford operators. The Pauli and Clifford groups play a crucial role \
in quantum error-correction codes and in many other areas of quantum \
computation and quantum information. See also Section 6.3 of the Quantum \
Workbook (2022).", "synonyms" -> {}, "tabletags" -> {}, "title" -> 
    "The Pauli and Clifford Groups", "titlemodifier" -> "", "metadescription" -> 
    "", "windowtitle" -> "The Pauli and Clifford Groups", "type" -> 
    "Tech Note", "uri" -> "QuantumMob/Q3/tutorial/PauliAndCliffordGroups"}},
